Association Rules

Viktor Sas

2024-01-20

Introduction

In the following report, I am analyzing the association rules between products separetely at supermarkets and at convenient stores to see how the purchase of certain products have an impact on the likelihood of purchasing other goods.

I used the following dataset during the analysis:

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/prasad22/retail-transactions-dataset?resource=download

The dataset is well documented under the above mentioned link, therefore I am not going into too much details. However, it is worth to note that the original dataset contains data from many different kinds of stores. In order to gain a clearer picture, I decided to not analyse the whole dataset as one, instead, I created two sub datasets which contain data regarding purchases made at supermarkets and purchases made at convenience stores.

Since we have around 5000 supermarket and 5000 convienience store transactions and the relative occurance of our products are low, under 0.08, I chose a low support and confidence level to find the association rules.

After reorganizing our supermarket rules by lift, we notice that Syrup and Tea have the highest lift (2,42 which is considered a strong lift), meaning in case Syrup is placed in the basket, there is a very high chance that the customer would also purchase Tea. Logically thinking, probably ill customers buy syrup to cure their sore throat or cough and they likely pair this purchase with tea, which is also an often used remedy. In general, a lift greater than 1 indicates that there is a positive association between the two products.

According to the association rules based on Shampoo, in case someone purchases Shampoo in the convenient store, there is a good chance they would also purchase other hygiene related products such as Toothpaste, Shaving Cream, Trash Bags and Dish Soap.

Summary:

Thanks to different methods of association rules we can have an insight into the choices of customers and their purchasing “path”, we can also discover which products likely “trigger” the purchase of other products. Based on these insights supermarkets can make informed decisions for example about the organisation of products in their stores.
